    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Something About That Colorful Salmon</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ellen Schneider letter warns that bright color on farm-raised salmon comes from food dyes (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your May 14 editorial about genetically altered salmon -- ''hormonally hyperactive creatures'' -- brought to mind a collateral issue: the lack of regulations requiring disclosure pertaining to the feedstuffs on which farm-raised fish are grown.</p>
        <p>I was shocked to learn from my fish seller, for example, that the ''normal'' farm-raised salmon I had been buying had obtained its beautiful red-orange hue from food dyes.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your May 14 editorial about genetically altered salmon -- ''hormonally hyperactive creatures'' -- brought to mind a collateral issue: the lack of regulations requiring disclosure pertaining to the feedstuffs on which farm-raised fish are grown.</p>
        <p>I was shocked to learn from my fish seller, for example, that the ''normal'' farm-raised salmon I had been buying had obtained its beautiful red-orange hue from food dyes.</p>
        <p>What other surprises lurk within the flesh of the fish that the health gurus have, of late, been so urgently urging us to consume?</p>
        <p>ELLEN SCHNEIDER  Fort Lauderdale, Fla., May 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
